"One America, Two Peoples"
New York — As I write this, officials across the United States are still counting votes for the 2020 presidential election.
Once the statistical results are finally confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
In this closely contested and record-turnout election, that was to be expected.
Only U.S. citizens can vote to elect their President, but this choice affects people around the world.
If it is still too early to determine the election results, it is not too early, however, to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite actual restrictions related to the pandemic, voter participation rates remained high.
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
And violent incidents are rare.
The court is investigating the U.S. Postal Service's decision, which seems to be motivated by political considerations and involves hindering the delivery of ballots expected to come primarily from Democratic-leaning areas.
US President Donald Trump's unfounded declaration of victory on Tuesday evening received little response, and his request to stop counting votes (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to be falling on deaf ears.
However, worryingly, the divide among American voters remains significant.
The votes for the two candidates were almost equal.
It is not surprising that such division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trends continue, the Democrats will win the White House and maintain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
The governorship and seats in the state legislature are nearly evenly split between the two parties (with a slight advantage for the Republicans).
The expected "blue wave" for the Democrats did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, securing around 40-50 million votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But the Republicans held onto many seats that many had predicted they would flip in the Senate, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not stem from tough authorization nor from political adjustments.
Trump's polling numbers are excellent, with over 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote getter in U.S. presidential history and surpassing all previous winners.
It is particularly noteworthy that this occurred against the backdrop of record-breaking daily新增 cases and over 1,000 daily deaths.   For a more natural English flow, you might say:  "It is particularly noteworthy that this happened in the context of record-breaking daily increases in COVID-19 cases (over 100,000 new cases) and daily deaths (over 1,000)."
Just as the consequences of its government's mishandling of the pandemic were becoming most severe, nearly half of voters turned against him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he continues to stay in the public eye, which also seems possible.
Even if he does not run himself, he is likely to have a considerable influence on the choice of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican party will be far removed from the party of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
-Trumpism, a modern brand of American populism, will still be a powerful force.
As expected, despite Trump failing to produce any evidence, he has nevertheless strived to portray himself as upright and honest, attempting to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accusing others of fraudulent activities.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden's presidency as legitimate.
Trump is very likely never to concede, let alone attend the inauguration ceremony of the successor.
In Will Rogers' words, Trump has never run into a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions among those with similar views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the absence of a national civics curriculum facilitates the differentiation among generations.
It is worth stressing that the division within countries is not typically along economic lines.
People from all strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns did not align as many predicted along lines of population, gender, and race.
Their main disagreement lies in the remedial measures.
Educational attainment is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geography. Republican voters tend to reside in exurbs and rural areas, while Democrats tend to live in urban areas.
Nevertheless, the role of culture in American politics may be larger than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy did not seem to be particularly important in the campaign, aside from mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In such a context, it is difficult to win public support for major reforms in the way presidents are elected or government functions.
This situation is no different from that of reforming the United Nations Security Council.
Many believe that the current system has severe flaws, lacking in representation, but it is impossible to reach consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
As expected, those who will suffer losses due to the change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This is to a large extent dependent on Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell and his ability and willingness to cooperate with a future Biden presidency.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly face resistance from more ideologically rigid members of his own political party.
The Democrats had tried to dismiss Trump and everything his representatives stood for with sharp rebuttals.
But they were not successful.
And the Republicans are seeking an election in which Trump is validated.
And this did not turn out as they had wished.
Conversely, elections reveal two nations within one country.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can do so remains to be seen.
